<subsection xml:id="subsection-quadratic-change-form">
	<title>Forms</title>

	<p>We have solved quadratics using the (standard) form <m>ax^2+bx+c=0</m> and graphed parabolas using the form <m>a(x-h)^2+k</m>. From the form we used for graphing we can easily identify the vertex. With some effort it is possible to find the vertex from the standard form. We will look at a method that does not require using more algebra than we have practiced here.</p>

	<example xml:id="example-quadratic-standard-vertex">
		<statement><p>Find the vertex of <m>y=2x^2-11x+12</m>.</p></statement>
		<solution><p>Because of the symmetry of a parabola we know that the vertex lies half way between any pair of points with the same height. For example it is half way between the solutions to <m>2x^2-11x+12 = 0</m>.
			<md>
				<mrow>x &amp; = \frac{-(-11) \pm \sqrt{(-11)^2-4(2)(12)}}{2(2)}</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = \frac{11 \pm \sqrt{121-96}}{4}</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = \frac{11 \pm \sqrt{25}}{4}</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = \frac{11 \pm 5}{4}</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = 4, 3/2.</mrow>
			</md>
		To find what is half way in between we average these two values. 
			<md>
				<mrow>x &amp; = \frac{4+3/2}{2}</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = \frac{8/2+3/2}{2}</mrow>
				<mrow> &amp; = 11/4</mrow>
			</md>
		Thus the x-coordinate of the vertex is 11/4. To find the y-coordinate we substitute the x value into the quadratic.
			<me>2(11/4)^2-11(11/4)+12 = -25/8.</me></p>
		</solution>
	</example>

</subsection>

